40|$|This paper investigates empirically the {{persistence}} in <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regimes</b> {{as well as}} the role of capital account openness and financial sector health (measured by financial development and financial sector fragility) in <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime</b> determination for a panel of 143 countries covering the post-Bretton Woods period. The results demonstrate that while low- and high-income countries exhibit highly persistent <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regimes,</b> middle-income countries display relatively lower persistence. For middle-income countries, capital account openness and the level of financial development play important roles in <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime</b> choice. The fragility of the financial sector does not affect the <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime</b> determination...|$|R
