40|$|This paper {{examines}} {{the question of}} how to design an optimal and sustainable <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime</b> in a world economy of two interdependent countries. It develops a Barro-Gordon type two-country model and compares noncooperative equilibria under different assumptions of monetary policy credibility and different <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regimes.</b> Using a two-stage game approach to the strategic choice of policy instruments, it identifies optimal (in a Pare to sense) and sustainable (self-enforcing) <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regimes.</b> The theoretical results indicate that the choice of such regimes depends fundamentally on the credibility of monetary policy commitments by the two countries’ authorities. The nature of shocks to the economies and the substitutability between goods produced in the two countries also play some role. International coordination on instrument choice is necessary to design optimal and sustainable <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regimes.</b> <b>Exchange</b> rate regimes;Economic models;exchange rate, <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime,</b> inflation, money supply, monetary policy, fixed exchange rate, fixed <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime,</b> <b>exchange</b> rates, real output, flexible exchange rate, exchange rate stability, flexible <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regime,</b> <b>exchange</b> rate management, rate of inflation, fixed exchange rates, exchange rate commitment, price inflation, exchange rate rule, currency areas, rational expectations, nominal interest rate, price stability, inflationary policy, inflation rate, spot exchange rate, inflationary pressure, home currency, currency depreciation, optimal <b>exchange</b> rate <b>regimes,</b> foreign <b>exchange,</b> high inflation, exchange rate system, variable inflation, currency appreciation, real interest rate, spot exchange rates, real exchange rates, low inflation, exchange rate fluctuations, real exchange rate, monetary economics, alternative <b>exchange</b> rate <b>reg